==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Obvention
<hw>Ob*ven"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>obvention</ets>, fr. <ets>obvenire</ets> to come before or in the
way of, to befall; <ets>ob</ets> (see <er>Ob-</er>) + <ets>venire</ets>
to come: cf. F. <ets>obvention</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of happening
incidentally; that which happens casually; an incidental advantage; an
occasional offering.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Tithes and other
<xex>obventions</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Legacies bequeathed by the deaths of princes and great persons,
and other casualities and <qex>obventions</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

